olarship\nat Dallas Baptist University, Dallas, TX\nAwarded by the Dean of the College of Fine Arts to music majors who are pursuing vocal studies as their major area of applied music. Students must demonstrate financial need by completing the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA).\n\n{{cooper-surname}}\n\n{{surname|Boettcher}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boettcher}}\n[[Category:German-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Occupational surnames]]\n", "text_old": "{{wiktionary|B\u00f6ttcher}}\n'''Bottcher.''' or '''B\u00f6ttcher''' is a German surname. Notable people with the surname include:\n\n* [[Albrecht B\u00f6ttcher]] (born 1954), German mathematician\n* [[Arthur B\u00f6ttcher]] (1831\u20131889), German pathologist  and anatomist\n* [[August Friedrich B\u00f6ttcher]] (1825\u20131900), insect dealer in Berlin\n* [[Bas B\u00f6ttcher]] (born 1974), German slam poet\n* [[Brendan Bottcher]] (born 1991), Canadian curler\n* [[Champ Boettcher]] (1900\u20131965), American football player\n* [[Charles Boettcher]] (1852\u20131948), German-born Colorado businessman and philanthropist\n* [[Curt Boettcher]] (1944\u20131987), American singer, songwriter, musician and record producer\n* [[Grit Boettcher]] (born 1938), German actress\n* [[G\u00fcnter B\u00f6ttcher]] (1954\u20132012), West German handball player\n* [[Herman Bottcher]] (1909\u20131944), American soldier born in Germany\n* [[Hermann B\u00f6ttcher]] (1866\u20131935), German stage and film actor\n* [[J\u00fcrgen B\u00f6ttcher]] (born 1931), German film director and painter\n* [[Karl B\u00f6ttcher]] (1886\u20131974), German general\n* [[Lucjan B\u00f6ttcher]] (1872\u20131937), Polish mathematician\n* [[Markus B\u00f6ttcher]] (born 1964), German television actor\n* [[Martin B\u00f6ttcher]] (born 1927), German composer and conductor\n* [[Maximilian B\u00f6ttcher]] (1872\u20131950), German writer\n* [[Mike Boettcher]] (born 1954), American journalist and war correspondent\n* [[Paul B\u00f6ttcher]] (1912\u20131998), highly decorated lieutenant in the Wehrmacht during World War I\n\n== See also ==\n* [[B\u00f6ttcher America]], subsidiary of the German firm Felix B\u00f6ttcher GmbH\n* [[Boettcher Memorial Tropical Conservatory]]\n* [[Boettcher cell]]\n* [[B\u00f6ttcher's equation|B\u00f6ttcher's equation and function]]\n* [[Helena Boettcher]], athlete\n* [[Boettcher Concert Hall]]\n* [[Boettcher Scholarship]]\n\nEdmund F. Boettcher Vocal Scholarship\nat Dallas Baptist Univerity, Dallas, TX\nAwarded by the Dean of the College of Fine Arts to music majors who are pursuing vocal studies as their major area of applied music. Students must demonstrate financial need by completing the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA).\n\n{{cooper-surname}}\n\n{{surname|Boettcher}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boettcher}}\n[[Category:German-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Occupational surnames]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Univerity \u2192 University", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boettcher"}
{"title_page": "Condiment", "text_new": "{{Short description|Substance added to food to impart or enhance a flavor}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2015}}\n[[Image:Salt, sugar and pepper shakers.jpg|thumb|[[Salt]], [[black pepper|pepper]], and [[sugar]] are commonly placed on Western restaurant tables.]]\nA '''condiment''' is a [[spice]], [[sauce]], or preparation (such as onions) that is added to food, typically after cooking, to impart a specific [[flavor]], to enhance the flavor,<ref>Merriam-Webster: Definition of condiment</ref> or to complement the dish. A '''table condiment''' or '''table sauce''' is more specifically a condiment that is served separately from the food and is added to taste by the diner.\n\nCondiments are sometimes added prior to serving, for example, in a [[sandwich]] made with [[ketchup]], [[mustard (condiment)|mustard]] or [[mayonnaise]]. Some condiments are used during cooking to add flavor or texture: [[barbecue sauce]], [[compound butter]], [[Teriyaki#Teriyaki sauce|teriyaki sauce]], [[soy sauce]], and [[marmite]] and sour cream are examples.\n\nMany condiments, such as mustard or ketchup, are available in [[Packet (container)|single-serving packets]], commonly when supplied with [[take-out]] or [[Fast food|fast-food]] meals.\n\n==Definition==\n[[File:Typical Polish set of spices.jpg|thumb|Tray of condiments and spices]]\n[[File:ASC Leiden - W.E.A. van Beek Collection - Dogon markets 08 - Various condiments at Sangha market, Mali 1992.jpg|thumb|Various condiments at Sangha market, Mali 1992]]\nThe exact definition of a condiment varies. Some definitions encompass spices and herbs, including salt and pepper,<ref>Collins: Definition Condiment</ref> using the term interchangeably with ''seasoning''.<ref name=\"Farrell, p. 291\">Farrell, p. 291</ref> Others restrict the definition to include only \"prepared food compound[s], containing one or more spices\", which are added to food after the cooking process, such as mustard, ketchup or [[mint sauce]].<ref name=\"Farrell, p. 291\"/> Cheese is also considered a condiment in some European countries.{{Citation needed|reason=No citation granted|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Etymology==\n\nThe term ''condiment'' comes from the Latin ''condimentum'', meaning \"spice, seasoning, sauce\" and from the Latin ''condire'', meaning \"preserve, pickle, season\".<ref name=\"Nealon\">Nealon</ref> The term originally described pickled or preserved foods, but its meaning has changed over time.<ref>Smith, pp. 144\u2013146</ref>\n\n==History==\nCondiments were known in [[Ancient Rome]], [[Ancient India]], [[Ancient Greece]] and [[Ancient China]].   There is a myth that before food preservation techniques were widespread, pungent spices and condiments were used to make the food more palatable,<ref>Farrell, p. 297</ref> but this claim is not supported by any evidence or historical record.<ref>According to Paul Freedman, the idea is presented as a fact even by some modern scholars, despite the lack of any credible support; Freedman (2008), pp. 3\u20134</ref> The Romans made the condiments [[garum]] and [[liquamen]] by crushing the innards of various fish and then ferment it in salt, resulting in a liquid containing glutamic acid, suitable for enhancing the flavor of food. This process would lead to a flourishing condiment industry.<ref name=\"Nealon\"/> ''[[Apicius]]'', a [[cookbook]] based on fourth and fifth century cuisine, contains a section based solely on condiments.<ref name=\"Nealon\"/>\n\n==List of condiments==\n{{main|List of condiments}}\n{{see also|List of brand name condiments}}\n\n==Condiment market in the United States ==\n\nIn the [[United States]], the market for condiments was US$5.6 billion in 2010 and is estimated to grow to US$7 billion by 2015.<ref name=\"BB1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/10_42/b4199096744538.htm|title=Spreading the Love|last=Sax|first=David|date=October 7, 2010<!--, 5:00PM EST-->|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=9 October 2010}}</ref> The condiment market is the second largest in [[specialty foods]] behind that of cheese.<ref name=\"BB1\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Dijon mustard on a spoon - 20051218.jpg|[[Dijon mustard#Dijon mustard|Dijon mustard]]\nImage:Chrain3.jpg|[[Chrain]] ([[horseradish]] sauce)\nImage:Oeufsmayo.JPG|[[Mayonnaise]]\nImage:Ketchup-01.jpg|[[Tomato Ketchup]]\nImage:BasilkumPesto.jpg|[[Pesto]] [[Genoa|genovese]]\nImage:Chutneys.jpg|[[Chutney]]s\nImage:HAT YAI MARKET 2.jpg|[[Curry powder]] or [[Indian curry|paste]]\nImage:Megrelian ajika.jpg|[[Ajika]], spicy sauce in [[Caucasian cuisine]]\nImage:Tkemali.JPG|[[Tkemali]] ([[Georgian cuisine|Georgian]] sauce made of sour [[cherry plum]]s)\nImage:Chinese condiments at the restaurant by bhollar in Nerima, Tokyo.jpg|Common [[Chinese cuisine|Chinese]] condiments: [[soy sauce]], [[vinegar]], [[chili oil]], [[black pepper|white pepper]]\nImage:Duck sauce packets.jpg|Packets of [[duck sauce]]\nImage:Worcester Sauce 001.jpg|[[Worcestershire sauce]]\nImage:Relish.jpg|[[Gentleman's Relish]]\nImage:Flying goose sriracha th.jpg|[[Sriracha sauce|Sriracha]] (type of [[Hot sauce]])\nImage:Shichimi tougarashi.JPG|[[Shichimi]]\nImage:HK \u5317\u89d2 North Point \u548c\u7530 Wada Japanese Restaurant \u653e\u984c Buffet dinner \u5c71\u8475 green Wasabi Mar-2013.JPG|[[Wasabi]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[:Category:Condiments by country|Condiments by country]] (category)\n* {{annotated link|Dip (food)|Dip}}\n* {{annotated link|Garnish (food)|Garnish}}\n* {{annotated link|List of fish sauces}}\n* {{annotated link|List of foods}}\n* {{annotated link|List of mustard brands}}\n* {{annotated link|Non-brewed condiment}}\n* {{annotated link|Seasoning}}\n* {{annotated link|Spice}}\n* {{annotated link|Relish}}\n* {{annotated link|Ingredient}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url = http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/condiment?showCookiePolicy=true |title = Collins: Definition Condiment |publisher=Collins Dictionary |date = n.d. |accessdate=29 September 2014 }}\n* {{cite book |title = Spices, Condiments and Seasonings |page=291 |last=Farrell |first = K. T. |edition=2nd |year=1990 |location = MA, USA |publisher = Aspen Publishers |ISBN = 9780834213371 }}\n* {{cite web |url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/condiment |title = Merriam-Webster: Definition of condiment |publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary |accessdate=October 23, 2011 }}\n* {{cite web |url = http://hilobrow.com/2010/09/07/de-condimentis-1/ |title = De Condimentis |publisher=HiLobrow |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=10 February 2014 |first=Tom |last=Nealon }}\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=Andrew F. |title = The Oxford companion to American food and drink |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AoWlCmNDA3QC&pg=PT171 |accessdate = March 15, 2012 |date = May 1, 2007 |publisher = Oxford University Press |ISBN = 978-0-19-530796-2 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Condiments}}\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Tomatoes}}\n{{Veganism and vegetarianism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Condiments| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Substance added to food to impart or enhance a flavor}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2015}}\n[[Image:Salt, sugar and pepper shakers.jpg|thumb|[[Salt]], [[black pepper|pepper]], and [[sugar]] are commonly placed on Western restaurant tables.]]\nA '''condiment''' is a [[spice]], [[sauce]], or preparation (such as onions) that is added to food, typically after cooking, to impart a specific [[flavor]], to enhance the flavor,<ref>Merriam-Webster: Definition of condiment</ref> or to complement the dish. A '''table condiment''' or '''table sauce''' is more specifically a condiment that is served separately from the food and is added to taste by the diner.\n\nCondiments are sometimes added prior to serving, for example, in a [[sandwich]] made with [[ketchup]], [[mustard (condiment)|mustard]] or [[mayonnaise]]. Some condiments are used during cooking to add flavor or texture: [[barbecue sauce]], [[compound butter]], [[Teriyaki#Teriyaki sauce|teriyaki sauce]], [[soy sauce]], and [[marmite]] and sour cream are examples.\n\nMany condiments, such as mustard or ketchup, are available in [[Packet (container)|single-serving packets]], commonly when supplied with [[take-out]] or [[Fast food|fast-food]] meals.\n\n==Definition==\n[[File:Typical Polish set of spices.jpg|thumb|Tray of condiments and spices]]\n[[File:ASC Leiden - W.E.A. van Beek Collection - Dogon markets 08 - Various condiments at Sangha market, Mali 1992.jpg|thumb|Various condiments at Sangha market, Mali 1992]]\nThe exact definition of a condiment varies. Some definitions encompass spices and herbs, including salt pepper,<ref>Collins: Definition Condiment</ref> using the term interchangeably with ''seasoning''.<ref name=\"Farrell, p. 291\">Farrell, p. 291</ref> Others restrict the definition to include only \"prepared food compound[s], containing one or more spices\", which are added to food after the cooking process, such as mustard, ketchup or [[mint sauce]].<ref name=\"Farrell, p. 291\"/> Cheese is also considered a condiment in some European countries.{{Citation needed|reason=No citation granted|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Etymology==\n\nThe term ''condiment'' comes from the Latin ''condimentum'', meaning \"spice, seasoning, sauce\" and from the Latin ''condire'', meaning \"preserve, pickle, season\".<ref name=\"Nealon\">Nealon</ref> The term originally described pickled or preserved foods, but its meaning has changed over time.<ref>Smith, pp. 144\u2013146</ref>\n\n==History==\nCondiments were known in [[Ancient Rome]], [[Ancient India]], [[Ancient Greece]] and [[Ancient China]].   There is a myth that before food preservation techniques were widespread, pungent spices and condiments were used to make the food more palatable,<ref>Farrell, p. 297</ref> but this claim is not supported by any evidence or historical record.<ref>According to Paul Freedman, the idea is presented as a fact even by some modern scholars, despite the lack of any credible support; Freedman (2008), pp. 3\u20134</ref> The Romans made the condiments [[garum]] and [[liquamen]] by crushing the innards of various fish and then ferment it in salt, resulting in a liquid containing glutamic acid, suitable for enhancing the flavor of food. This process would lead to a flourishing condiment industry.<ref name=\"Nealon\"/> ''[[Apicius]]'', a [[cookbook]] based on fourth and fifth century cuisine, contains a section based solely on condiments.<ref name=\"Nealon\"/>\n\n==List of condiments==\n{{main|List of condiments}}\n{{see also|List of brand name condiments}}\n\n==Condiment market in the United States ==\n\nIn the [[United States]], the market for condiments was US$5.6 billion in 2010 and is estimated to grow to US$7 billion by 2015.<ref name=\"BB1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/10_42/b4199096744538.htm|title=Spreading the Love|last=Sax|first=David|date=October 7, 2010<!--, 5:00PM EST-->|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=9 October 2010}}</ref> The condiment market is the second largest in [[specialty foods]] behind that of cheese.<ref name=\"BB1\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Dijon mustard on a spoon - 20051218.jpg|[[Dijon mustard#Dijon mustard|Dijon mustard]]\nImage:Chrain3.jpg|[[Chrain]] ([[horseradish]] sauce)\nImage:Oeufsmayo.JPG|[[Mayonnaise]]\nImage:Ketchup-01.jpg|[[Tomato Ketchup]]\nImage:BasilkumPesto.jpg|[[Pesto]] [[Genoa|genovese]]\nImage:Chutneys.jpg|[[Chutney]]s\nImage:HAT YAI MARKET 2.jpg|[[Curry powder]] or [[Indian curry|paste]]\nImage:Megrelian ajika.jpg|[[Ajika]], spicy sauce in [[Caucasian cuisine]]\nImage:Tkemali.JPG|[[Tkemali]] ([[Georgian cuisine|Georgian]] sauce made of sour [[cherry plum]]s)\nImage:Chinese condiments at the restaurant by bhollar in Nerima, Tokyo.jpg|Common [[Chinese cuisine|Chinese]] condiments: [[soy sauce]], [[vinegar]], [[chili oil]], [[black pepper|white pepper]]\nImage:Duck sauce packets.jpg|Packets of [[duck sauce]]\nImage:Worcester Sauce 001.jpg|[[Worcestershire sauce]]\nImage:Relish.jpg|[[Gentleman's Relish]]\nImage:Flying goose sriracha th.jpg|[[Sriracha sauce|Sriracha]] (type of [[Hot sauce]])\nImage:Shichimi tougarashi.JPG|[[Shichimi]]\nImage:HK \u5317\u89d2 North Point \u548c\u7530 Wada Japanese Restaurant \u653e\u984c Buffet dinner \u5c71\u8475 green Wasabi Mar-2013.JPG|[[Wasabi]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[:Category:Condiments by country|Condiments by country]] (category)\n* {{annotated link|Dip (food)|Dip}}\n* {{annotated link|Garnish (food)|Garnish}}\n* {{annotated link|List of fish sauces}}\n* {{annotated link|List of foods}}\n* {{annotated link|List of mustard brands}}\n* {{annotated link|Non-brewed condiment}}\n* {{annotated link|Seasoning}}\n* {{annotated link|Spice}}\n* {{annotated link|Relish}}\n* {{annotated link|Ingredient}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url = http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/condiment?showCookiePolicy=true |title = Collins: Definition Condiment |publisher=Collins Dictionary |date = n.d. |accessdate=29 September 2014 }}\n* {{cite book |title = Spices, Condiments and Seasonings |page=291 |last=Farrell |first = K. T. |edition=2nd |year=1990 |location = MA, USA |publisher = Aspen Publishers |ISBN = 9780834213371 }}\n* {{cite web |url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/condiment |title = Merriam-Webster: Definition of condiment |publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary |accessdate=October 23, 2011 }}\n* {{cite web |url = http://hilobrow.com/2010/09/07/de-condimentis-1/ |title = De Condimentis |publisher=HiLobrow |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=10 February 2014 |first=Tom |last=Nealon }}\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=Andrew F. |title = The Oxford companion to American food and drink |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AoWlCmNDA3QC&pg=PT171 |accessdate = March 15, 2012 |date = May 1, 2007 |publisher = Oxford University Press |ISBN = 978-0-19-530796-2 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Condiments}}\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Tomatoes}}\n{{Veganism and vegetarianism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Condiments| ]]\n", "name_user": "Keith meef", "label": "safe", "comment": "missing \"and\" between \"salt pepper\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Condiment"}
{"title_page": "Taibe, Israel", "text_new": "{{for|other places with similar names|Taybeh (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Israel village\n| name = Taibe\n| image = 2010.11.06 07M Taibe.jpg\n| caption = Taibe, 2010\n| hebname = {{Hebrew|\u05d8\u05b7\u05bc\u05d9\u05b4\u05bc\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}\n| arname = \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628\u0629\u200e\n| meaning = \n| foundation = \n| district = north\n| council = [[Gilboa Regional Council|Gilboa]]\n| palgrid = 192/223\n| popyear  = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Tayibe(baemeq)}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Israel populations|reference}}\n| pushpin_map = Israel jezreel | pushpin_mapsize = 250 | pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| coordinates = {{coord|32|36|N|35|26|E|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Taibe''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628\u0629}}; {{lang-he-n|\u05d8\u05b7\u05bc\u05d9\u05b4\u05bc\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}), meaning \"The goodly\",<ref>Palmer, 1881, [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp00conduoft#page/167/mode/1up p.167]</ref> is a [[Muslim]] [[Arab]] village in northeastern [[Israel]]. Located in the [[Jezreel Valley]], it falls under the jurisdiction of [[Gilboa Regional Council]]. In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Tayibe(baemeq)}}.{{Israel populations|reference}} \n\n==History==\n[[File:Taibe Village View.jpg|thumb|250px|Taibe village view]]\n\n===Israelite era===\nIt has been proposed that Taibe was '''Tubi''', listed among the places paying tribute to [[Thutmose III]].<ref name=SWP87/> Historical geographer [[Yeshayahu Press]] thought the site to be the biblical [[Hapharaim]] mentioned in the [[Torah]] in Joshua 19:19 in connection with the tribe of [[Tribe of Issachar|Issachar]], by a reversion of its name from what sounded like ''Afrin'' (\"demons\") to a euphemistic sound (lit. \"the goodly\"), as was common in other Arabic place-names.<ref>[[Ishtori Haparchi]], ''Kaftor u'ferach'' vol. 2,  (3rd edition, published by ed. Avraham Yosef Havatzelet), chapter 11, Jerusalem 2007, p. 63 (note 144) (Hebrew)</ref> Remains from the Israelite, Hellenistic, Roman, Byzantine, Crusader, and Mamluk periods have been found.<ref name=\"Hadashot\">Covello-Paran and  Tepper, 2008,  [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=871&mag_id=114 Et-Taiyiba]</ref><ref>Tepper, 2012,  [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1987&mag_id=119 E-Taiyiba, Survey Final Report]</ref> \n\n===Roman and Byzantine era===\nNorth east of the village  [[sarcophagus]] remains have been found. This area apparently functioned as a graveyard during the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and  [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] eras.<ref>Mokary, 2017,  [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=25223&mag_id=125 Et-Taiyiba, Horbat Haddad]</ref>\n \n===Crusader era===\nDuring the [[Crusades|Crusader]] period there was a castle here called (Le) '''Forbelet''' (in medieval Arabic: 'Afrabala).<ref name=\"Pringle\">Pringle, 1997, p.  [https://books.google.ca/books?id=-_NbE5obqRMC&pg=PA104 104]</ref> It was probably [[Hospitaller]] and dependent on nearby [[Belvoir Fortress (Israel)|Belvoir]].<ref name=\"Pringle\"/>  [[Yaqut al-Hamawi|Yaqut]]  (1179\u20131229) noted about the village, which he called ''Afrabala'': \"A place in the Jordan Ghaur (or low-land), near [[Baisan]] and [[Tabariyyah]].\"<ref>le Strange, 1890, p. [https://archive.org/stream/palestineundermo00lestuoft#page/385/mode/1up 385]</ref>\n\nIn July 1182 the castle was the background of the pitched large-scale Battle of Forbelet between [[Baldwin IV of Jerusalem|Baldwin IV]] and [[Saladin]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Corliss K. Slack |year=2013 |title=Historical Dictionary of the Crusades |location=Plymouth |publisher=Scarecrow Press of Rowman & Littlefield |page=51 |isbn=978-0-8108-7830-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uX8e2zU_TG0C&pg=PA51 |quote= |accessdate=2 January 2015 }}</ref> The castle was sacked by [[Saladin]] in 1183, and occupied by the [[Muslim]]s besieging Belvoir in 1187-88.<ref name=\"Pringle\"/> Parts of the castle [[keep]]'s basement still survive, as do other installations from the Crusader Period.<ref name=\"Hadashot\"/><ref name=\"Pringle\"/> Recent excavations indicate that new buildings were constructed alongside the partially destroyed Crusader castle in  [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] and Ottoman times.<ref>Abu Zidan, 2011, [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1664&mag_id=118 Et-Taiyiba Final Report]</ref>\n\n===Ottoman era===\nTaibe was incorporated into the [[Ottoman Empire]] in 1517 with all of Palestine, and in 1596 it appeared in the  [[daftar|tax registers]] under the name of  ''Tayyibat al-Ism''  as being in the ''[[Nahiya]]'' of Shafa of the ''[[Liwa (Arabic)|Liwa]]'' of [[Lajjun]]. It had a population of 13 [[Muslim]] households and paid taxes on wheat, barley, summer crops, and goats or beehives; a total of 5,300 [[Ak\u00e7e]].<ref>H\u00fctteroth and  Abdulfattah, 1977, p. 157</ref> [[Pierre Jacotin]] named  the village ''Taibeh'' on his map from 1799.<ref>Karmon, 1960, p. [http://www.jchp.ucla.edu/Bibliography/Karmon,_Y_1960_Jacotin_Map_(IEJ_10).pdf 169]</ref>\n\nIn 1875, the French explorer [[Victor Gu\u00e9rin]] visited the village and described it as poor, but formerly an important city,<ref>Gu\u00e9rin, 1880, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr01unkngoog#page/n139/mode/2up 126\u2013127] as translated by Conder and Kitchener, 1882, SWP II, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/126/mode/1up 126] -127: \"This village, poor and miserable, is now nothing but a wretched relic of an  important city, situated on the slope of a hill whose summit was surrounded by a fortress. This was formerly constructed of very fine [[basalt]]ic blocks, cut and dressed with care ; a ditch cut in the rock and now three-fourths filled up surrounded it, at least on the south and west. There remain of this stronghold several thick parts of the wall, and within [[Vault (architecture)|vaulted]] magazines which now serve the [[fellahin]] for refuge : rude dwelling-houses have also been built within the inclosure. One of these houses, more considerable than the others, and partly constructed of good basaltic stones taken from the ruins of the fort, occupies the top of the acropolis, which I regard as ancient, although allowing that it may have received attention from the Mohammedans or the Crusaders. As for the city, which extended to the north and east of the castle, it now, with the exception of a few [[Course (architecture)|courses]] still upright, presents nothing but a heap of ruins.'</ref> while in 1882 the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]'s ''Survey of Western Palestine''  described Taibe  as: \"A straggling village, of moderate size, lying on flat ground, and containing several good stone houses. There is one in the middle of the village, belonging to the Sheikh, which is larger than the rest.\"<ref name=SWP87>Conder and Kitchener, 1882, SWP II, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/87/mode/1up 87]</ref>\n\n===British Mandate era===\n[[File:Taibe Village Mosque.jpg|thumb|200px|Taibe village mosque]]\nIn a [[1922 census of Palestine|census]] conducted in 1922 by the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate]] authorities, Taibeh had a population of 220, all Muslim,<ref name=\"Census1922\">Barron, 1923, Table IX, Sub-district of Baisan, p. [https://archive.org/stream/PalestineCensus1922/Palestine%20Census%20%281922%29#page/n33/mode/1up   31]</ref> while at the time of the [[1931 census of Palestine|1931 census]], At-Taiyiba had 43 occupied houses and a population of 186 Muslims.<ref name=\"Census1931\">Mills, 1932, p. [https://archive.org/details/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas   81]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Village Statistics, 1945|1945 statistics]]  Taibe had a population of 280 Muslims  (counted with 150 Jews at [[Moledet, Israel|Moledet]])<ref name=DoS1945>Department of Statistics, 1945, p. [http://users.cecs.anu.edu.au/~bdm/yabber/census/VSpages/VS1945_p07.jpg   7]</ref> with 7,127 [[dunam]]s of land, according to an official land and population survey.<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20I/Baysan/Page-044.jpg  44]</ref> Of this, 7,103 dunams were used for cereals,<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20II/Baysan/Page-085.jpg 85]</ref> while 22 dunams were built-up land.<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20III/Baysan/Page-135.jpg  135]</ref>\n\n===State of Israel===\nSince 1948 Taibe has been under Israeli rule. To mark Israel's 60th anniversary in 2008, the dome of the local mosque was painted in the Israeli colors, blue and white.<ref name=haaretz1>{{cite news |title=Galilee Arabs paint mosque blue and white for Israel's 60th |author= |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/galilee-arabs-paint-mosque-blue-and-white-for-israel-s-60th-1.243543 |newspaper=Haaretz |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=Maariv1>{{cite news |title=Identifying with the country: The mosque was painted blue and white|author=Dudu Bazak |url=http://www.nrg.co.il/online/1/ART1/718/996.html |newspaper=Maariv |date=4 July 2008 |accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nNearly all the residents of Taibe are members of the Zuabi family, one of the larger clans in Israel.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/business/arab-villagers-in-a-taibeh-struggle-to-be-accepted-as-israelis-1.336520 Arab villagers in A-Taibeh struggle to be accepted as Israelis] Haaretz, 12 January 2011\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arab localities in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Abu Zidan|first=Fadi|date= 2011-05-01 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1664&mag_id=118  |title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=123}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Atrash|first=Walid|date= 2015-02-26 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=15725&mag_id=122  |title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=127}}\n*{{cite book | editor =Barron,  J. B.  | title = Palestine: Report and General Abstracts of the Census of 1922|url=https://archive.org/details/PalestineCensus1922  | publisher = Government of Palestine | year = 1923}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Conder|first1=C.R.|authorlink1=Claude Reignier Conder|last2=Kitchener|first2=H.H.|authorlink2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|year=1882|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp02conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|location=London|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]|volume=2}}  \n*{{cite journal|last1=Covello-Paran|first1=Karen|last2=Tepper|first2=Yotam|authorlink2=Yotam Tepper|date= 2008-08-24 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=871&mag_id=114|title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report|publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=120}}\n*{{cite journal|last1= Dalali-Amos |first1=Edna |date= 2016-07-12 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=25017&mag_id=124 |title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report|publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=128}}\n*{{cite book|title=Village Statistics, April, 1945 |url=http://web.nli.org.il/sites/nli/Hebrew/library/Pages/BookReader.aspx?pid=856390|author=Department of Statistics|year=1945|publisher=Government of Palestine}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=V.|authorlink=Victor Gu\u00e9rin|title=Description G\u00e9ographique Historique et Arch\u00e9ologique de la Palestine|url=https://archive.org/details/descriptiongogr01unkngoog|volume=3: Galilee, pt. 1|year=1880|publisher= L'Imprimerie Nationale|location=Paris|language=French}} \n*{{cite book|title=Village Statistics of 1945: A Classification of Land and Area ownership in Palestine|url=http://www.palestineremembered.com/Articles/General-2/Story3150.html|first=S.|last=Hadawi|authorlink=Sami Hadawi|year=1970|publisher=Palestine Liberation Organization Research Center}} \n*{{cite book | last1= H\u00fctteroth |first1=Wolf-Dieter |first2=Kamal | last2=Abdulfattah | title = Historical Geography of Palestine, Transjordan and Southern Syria in the Late 16th Century |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wqULAAAAIAAJ  | year = 1977 | publisher = Erlanger Geographische Arbeiten, Sonderband 5. Erlangen, Germany: Vorstand der Fr\u00e4nkischen Geographischen Gesellschaft|isbn= 3-920405-41-2}}\n*{{cite journal | author =  Karmon, Y. | title = An Analysis of Jacotin's Map of Palestine|url=http://www.jchp.ucla.edu/Bibliography/Karmon,_Y_1960_Jacotin_Map_(IEJ_10).pdf | journal = Israel Exploration Journal | volume = 10 | issue = 3,4 | year = 1960 | pages = 155\u2013173; 244\u2013253}} \n*{{cite book | editor = Mills, E. | title = Census of Palestine 1931. Population of Villages, Towns and Administrative Areas |url=https://archive.org/details/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas | publisher = Government of Palestine | location = Jerusalem | year = 1932}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Mokary |first=Abdalla |date= 2017-06-19 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=25223&mag_id=125   |title=Et-Taiyiba, Horbat Haddad   |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=129}}\n*{{cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|authorlink=Edward Henry Palmer|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]}}\n*[https://archive.org/details/recueildeshistor04acad_0  RHC Or vol. 4], 1898,  [[Recueil des historiens des croisades]] (p.&nbsp;345, cf p.&nbsp;303)\n*{{cite book|title= Secular buildings in the Crusader Kingdom of Jerusalem: an archaeological Gazetter |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=-_NbE5obqRMC|first1=Denys|last1=Pringle|year=1997|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}} \n*{{cite book|title=Palestine Under the Moslems: A Description of Syria and the Holy Land from A.D. 650 to 1500|url=https://archive.org/details/palestineundermo00lestuoft |first=G.|last=Strange, le|authorlink=Guy Le Strange|year=1890|publisher=Committee of the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]}}  \n*{{cite journal|last=Tepper|first=Y. |authorlink=Yotam Tepper|date= 2012-04-16 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1987 |title=Et-Taiyiba, Survey, Final Report|publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=124}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Tepper|first1=Y.|authorlink1=Yotam Tepper|last2=Covello-Paran|first2=Karen|date= 2012-12-31 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=2200 |title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report|publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=124}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.palestineremembered.com/GeoPoints/al_Taiyiba_815/index.html  Welcome To Kh. al-Tayiba]\n*Survey of Western Palestine, Map 9: [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8371  IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.09.jpg Wikimedia commons], where it is listed as ''et Taiyibeh''\n\n{{Gilboa Regional Council}}\n{{Crusader sites}}\n\n[[Category:Arab villages in Israel]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Northern District (Israel)]]\n[[Category:Castles and fortifications of the Knights Hospitaller]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other places with similar names|Taybeh (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Israel village\n| name = Taibe\n| image = 2010.11.06 07M Taibe.jpg\n| caption = Taibe, 2010\n| hebname = {{Hebrew|\u05d8\u05b7\u05bc\u05d9\u05b4\u05bc\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}\n| arname = \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628\u0629\u200e\n| meaning = \n| foundation = \n| district = north\n| council = [[Gilboa Regional Council|Gilboa]]\n| palgrid = 192/223\n| popyear  = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Tayibe(baemeq)}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Israel populations|reference}}\n| pushpin_map = Israel jezreel | pushpin_mapsize = 250 | pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| coordinates = {{coord|32|36|N|35|26|E|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Taibe''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628\u0629}}; {{lang-he-n|\u05d8\u05b7\u05bc\u05d9\u05b4\u05bc\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}), meaning \"The goodly\",<ref>Palmer, 1881, [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp00conduoft#page/167/mode/1up p.167]</ref> is a [[Muslim]] [[Arab]] village in northeastern [[Israel]]. Located in the [[Jezreel Valley]], it falls under the jurisdiction of [[Gilboa Regional Council]]. In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Tayibe(baemeq)}}.{{Israel populations|reference}} \n\n==History==\n[[File:Taibe Village View.jpg|thumb|250px|Taibe village view]]\nIt has been proposed that Taibe was '''Tubi''', listed among the places paying tribute to [[Thutmose III]].<ref name=SWP87/> Historical geographer [[Yeshayahu Press]] thought the site to be the biblical [[Hapharaim]] mentioned in Joshua 19:19 in connection with the tribe of [[Tribe of Issachar|Issachar]], by a reversion of its name from what sounded like ''Afrin'' (\"demons\") to a euphemistic sound (lit. \"the goodly\"), as was common in other Arabic place-names.<ref>[[Ishtori Haparchi]], ''Kaftor u'ferach'' vol. 2,  (3rd edition, published by ed. Avraham Yosef Havatzelet), chapter 11, Jerusalem 2007, p. 63 (note 144) (Hebrew)</ref> Remains from the Hellenistic, Roman, Byzantine, Crusader, and Mamluk periods have been found.<ref name=\"Hadashot\">Covello-Paran and  Tepper, 2008,  [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=871&mag_id=114 Et-Taiyiba]</ref><ref>Tepper, 2012,  [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1987&mag_id=119 E-Taiyiba, Survey Final Report]</ref> North east of the village  [[sarcophagus]] remains have been found. This area apparently functioned as a graveyard during the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and  [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] eras.<ref>Mokary, 2017,  [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=25223&mag_id=125 Et-Taiyiba, Horbat Haddad]</ref>\n \nDuring the [[Crusades|Crusader]] period there was a castle here called (Le) '''Forbelet''' (in medieval Arabic: 'Afrabala).<ref name=\"Pringle\">Pringle, 1997, p.  [https://books.google.ca/books?id=-_NbE5obqRMC&pg=PA104 104]</ref> It was probably [[Hospitaller]] and dependent on nearby [[Belvoir Fortress (Israel)|Belvoir]].<ref name=\"Pringle\"/>  [[Yaqut al-Hamawi|Yaqut]]  (1179\u20131229) noted about the village, which he called ''Afrabala'': \"A place in the Jordan Ghaur (or low-land), near [[Baisan]] and [[Tabariyyah]].\"<ref>le Strange, 1890, p. [https://archive.org/stream/palestineundermo00lestuoft#page/385/mode/1up 385]</ref>\n\nIn July 1182 the castle was the background of the pitched large-scale Battle of Forbelet between [[Baldwin IV of Jerusalem|Baldwin IV]] and [[Saladin]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Corliss K. Slack |year=2013 |title=Historical Dictionary of the Crusades |location=Plymouth |publisher=Scarecrow Press of Rowman & Littlefield |page=51 |isbn=978-0-8108-7830-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uX8e2zU_TG0C&pg=PA51 |quote= |accessdate=2 January 2015 }}</ref> The castle was sacked by [[Saladin]] in 1183, and occupied by the [[Muslim]]s besieging Belvoir in 1187-88.<ref name=\"Pringle\"/> Parts of the castle [[keep]]'s basement still survive, as do other installations from the Crusader Period.<ref name=\"Hadashot\"/><ref name=\"Pringle\"/> Recent excavations indicate that new buildings were constructed alongside the partially destroyed Crusader castle in  [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] and Ottoman times.<ref>Abu Zidan, 2011, [http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1664&mag_id=118 Et-Taiyiba Final Report]</ref>\n\n===Ottoman era===\nTaibe was incorporated into the [[Ottoman Empire]] in 1517 with all of Palestine, and in 1596 it appeared in the  [[daftar|tax registers]] under the name of  ''Tayyibat al-Ism''  as being in the ''[[Nahiya]]'' of Shafa of the ''[[Liwa (Arabic)|Liwa]]'' of [[Lajjun]]. It had a population of 13 [[Muslim]] households and paid taxes on wheat, barley, summer crops, and goats or beehives; a total of 5,300 [[Ak\u00e7e]].<ref>H\u00fctteroth and  Abdulfattah, 1977, p. 157</ref> [[Pierre Jacotin]] named  the village ''Taibeh'' on his map from 1799.<ref>Karmon, 1960, p. [http://www.jchp.ucla.edu/Bibliography/Karmon,_Y_1960_Jacotin_Map_(IEJ_10).pdf 169]</ref>\n\nIn 1875, the French explorer [[Victor Gu\u00e9rin]] visited the village and described it as poor, but formerly an important city,<ref>Gu\u00e9rin, 1880, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr01unkngoog#page/n139/mode/2up 126\u2013127] as translated by Conder and Kitchener, 1882, SWP II, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/126/mode/1up 126] -127: \"This village, poor and miserable, is now nothing but a wretched relic of an  important city, situated on the slope of a hill whose summit was surrounded by a fortress. This was formerly constructed of very fine [[basalt]]ic blocks, cut and dressed with care ; a ditch cut in the rock and now three-fourths filled up surrounded it, at least on the south and west. There remain of this stronghold several thick parts of the wall, and within [[Vault (architecture)|vaulted]] magazines which now serve the [[fellahin]] for refuge : rude dwelling-houses have also been built within the inclosure. One of these houses, more considerable than the others, and partly constructed of good basaltic stones taken from the ruins of the fort, occupies the top of the acropolis, which I regard as ancient, although allowing that it may have received attention from the Mohammedans or the Crusaders. As for the city, which extended to the north and east of the castle, it now, with the exception of a few [[Course (architecture)|courses]] still upright, presents nothing but a heap of ruins.'</ref> while in 1882 the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]'s ''Survey of Western Palestine''  described Taibe  as: \"A straggling village, of moderate size, lying on flat ground, and containing several good stone houses. There is one in the middle of the village, belonging to the Sheikh, which is larger than the rest.\"<ref name=SWP87>Conder and Kitchener, 1882, SWP II, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/87/mode/1up 87]</ref>\n\n===British Mandate era===\n[[File:Taibe Village Mosque.jpg|thumb|200px|Taibe village mosque]]\nIn a [[1922 census of Palestine|census]] conducted in 1922 by the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate]] authorities, Taibeh had a population of 220, all Muslim,<ref name=\"Census1922\">Barron, 1923, Table IX, Sub-district of Baisan, p. [https://archive.org/stream/PalestineCensus1922/Palestine%20Census%20%281922%29#page/n33/mode/1up   31]</ref> while at the time of the [[1931 census of Palestine|1931 census]], At-Taiyiba had 43 occupied houses and a population of 186 Muslims.<ref name=\"Census1931\">Mills, 1932, p. [https://archive.org/details/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas   81]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Village Statistics, 1945|1945 statistics]]  Taibe had a population of 280 Muslims  (counted with 150 Jews at [[Moledet, Israel|Moledet]])<ref name=DoS1945>Department of Statistics, 1945, p. [http://users.cecs.anu.edu.au/~bdm/yabber/census/VSpages/VS1945_p07.jpg   7]</ref> with 7,127 [[dunam]]s of land, according to an official land and population survey.<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20I/Baysan/Page-044.jpg  44]</ref> Of this, 7,103 dunams were used for cereals,<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20II/Baysan/Page-085.jpg 85]</ref> while 22 dunams were built-up land.<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20III/Baysan/Page-135.jpg  135]</ref>\n\n===State of Israel===\nSince 1948 Taibe has been under Israeli rule. To mark Israel's 60th anniversary in 2008, the dome of the local mosque was painted in the Israeli colors, blue and white.<ref name=haaretz1>{{cite news |title=Galilee Arabs paint mosque blue and white for Israel's 60th |author= |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/galilee-arabs-paint-mosque-blue-and-white-for-israel-s-60th-1.243543 |newspaper=Haaretz |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=Maariv1>{{cite news |title=Identifying with the country: The mosque was painted blue and white|author=Dudu Bazak |url=http://www.nrg.co.il/online/1/ART1/718/996.html |newspaper=Maariv |date=4 July 2008 |accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nNearly all the residents of Taibe are members of the Zuabi family, one of the larger clans in Israel.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/business/arab-villagers-in-a-taibeh-struggle-to-be-accepted-as-israelis-1.336520 Arab villagers in A-Taibeh struggle to be accepted as Israelis] Haaretz, 12 January 2011\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arab localities in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Abu Zidan|first=Fadi|date= 2011-05-01 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1664&mag_id=118  |title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=123}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Atrash|first=Walid|date= 2015-02-26 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=15725&mag_id=122  |title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report |publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=127}}\n*{{cite book | editor =Barron,  J. B.  | title = Palestine: Report and General Abstracts of the Census of 1922|url=https://archive.org/details/PalestineCensus1922  | publisher = Government of Palestine | year = 1923}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Conder|first1=C.R.|authorlink1=Claude Reignier Conder|last2=Kitchener|first2=H.H.|authorlink2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|year=1882|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp02conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|location=London|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]|volume=2}}  \n*{{cite journal|last1=Covello-Paran|first1=Karen|last2=Tepper|first2=Yotam|authorlink2=Yotam Tepper|date= 2008-08-24 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=871&mag_id=114|title=Et-Taiyiba Final Report|publisher=Hadashot Arkheologiyot \u2013 Excavations and Surveys in Israel |number=120}}\n*{{cite journal|last1= Dalali-Amos |first1=Edna |date= 2016-07-12 |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.a